Farmers in the Eastern parts of the country should brace themselves for long dry spells in October and most of December, with significant rainfall expected during the peak month of November.In its August food security report, the Ministry of Agriculture forecasted a La Ni a condition, which peaks towards the end of the year and persists to the beginning of next year. The depressed, poorly distributed rainfall expected over most of the Eastern areas of the country will hurt agricultural activities. Farmers are advised to liaise with the Ministry of Agriculture, make best use of the rains by planting on time and select appropriate crops tolerant to low rainfall, the report states.Ministry director of crop management Johnson Irungu yesterday urged farmers to plant by mid October.The report warned that foliage and pasture in Northeastern, Northwestern and Southeastern Kenya are expected to deteriorate. It urged livestock departments to monitor the situation.